👉 File Handling in Java

Reading from & Writing to files is an important aspect of any programming language.
We can use the file class in java to crteate a file object

=> CreateNewFile() method -> creates a file object
=> for reading files we can use the same Scanner cvlass and supply it a file object
=> to delete a file in java we can use file object delete()

File Handling in Java is used to:

(1) create files
(2) read files
(3) write files
(4) update files
(5) delete files

Java provides the java.io package for file handling operations.

Important Classes in File Handling

| Class            | Purpose                 |
| ---------------- | ----------------------- |
| `File`           | Create and manage files |
| `FileWriter`     | Write data into file    |
| `FileReader`     | Read data from file     |
| `BufferedReader` | Read text efficiently   |
| `BufferedWriter` | Write text efficiently  |
| `Scanner`        | Read file data easily   |
| `PrintWriter`    | Write formatted data    |

👉 Import Statement

        import java.io.*;
        or
        import java.io.File;

👉 Creating a File

Using File class : Example

import java.io.File;
import java.io.IOException;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try{
            File myFile = new File("sample.txt");
            if(myFile.createNewFile()){
                System.out.println("File created successfully");
            }
            else{
                System.out.println("File already exists");
            }
        }
        catch(IOException e){
            System.out.println("Error occurred");
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}

Output : 
File created successfully

👉 Writing into a File : Using FileWriter.

import java.io.FileWriter;
import java.io.IOException;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try{
            FileWriter writer = new FileWriter("sample.txt");
            writer.write("Hello, Welcome to Java File Handling");
            writer.close();
            System.out.println("Successfully written into file");
        }

        catch(IOException e){
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}

👉 Reading from a File : Using Scanner.

import java.io.File;
import java.util.Scanner;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try{
            File myFile = new File("sample.txt");
            Scanner sc = new Scanner(myFile);
            while(sc.hasNextLine()){
                String line = sc.nextLine();
                System.out.println(line);
            }
            sc.close();
        }
        catch(Exception e){
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}

👉 Deleting a File

import java.io.File;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        File myFile = new File("sample.txt");
        if(myFile.delete()){
            System.out.println("File deleted");
        }
        else{
            System.out.println("Failed to delete");
        }
    }
}

👉 Methods of File Class
| Method              | Work                    |
| ------------------- | ----------------------- |
| `createNewFile()`   | Creates file            |
| `exists()`          | Checks file existence   |
| `delete()`          | Deletes file            |
| `getName()`         | Returns file name       |
| `getAbsolutePath()` | Returns full path       |
| `length()`          | Returns file size       |
| `canRead()`         | Checks read permission  |
| `canWrite()`        | Checks write permission |
